// Semantic direction:
// lambda_kalkulus is the minimal formal system underlying all functional programming languages.
// lk_abstraksjon λx.t binds x in t; lk_applikasjon (t u) applies function t to argument u.
// de_bruijn_indeks replaces variable names with depth counts — eliminates alpha-equivalence concerns.
// alfa_konvertering renames bound variables: λx.x =_α λy.y; they are semantically identical.
// captures_avoiding substituering avoids capturing free variables by renaming when needed.
// beta_reduksjon: (λx.t) u →_β t[x:=u] — apply the function by substituting the argument.
// eta_reduksjon: λx.(f x) →_η f when x ∉ FV(f) — extensional equality.
// normal_order evaluates the outermost, leftmost redex first — always finds a normal form if one exists.
// call_by_value evaluates arguments before passing — standard in most imperative languages.
// call_by_need is lazy evaluation with memoization — evaluates each argument at most once.
// church_rosser: if t →* u and t →* v, then ∃w such that u →* w and v →* w (confluence).
// sterk_normalisering: all reduction sequences terminate (no infinite loops).
// church_tall encodes natural numbers: 0 = λf.λx.x, 1 = λf.λx.f x, n = λf.λx.fⁿ x.
// y_kombinatoren: Y = λf.(λx.f(x x))(λx.f(x x)); Y f = f (Y f) — computes fixed points.
// subject_reduction: if Γ ⊢ t : A and t →_β t', then Γ ⊢ t' : A — types are preserved by reduction.
// progress_teorem: if ⊢ t : A, then either t is a value or t →_β t' for some t'.

// Primitive flow:
// beta_reduksjon (CBV): (λx. x + 1) 5
//   evaluer argument: 5 er verdi -> substituér: 5 + 1 -> 6
// Church tall multiplikasjon: mult = λm.λn.λf. m (n f)
//   mult 2 3 f = 2 (3 f) = (3 f) ((3 f) x) = 6 f-applikasjoner
// Y-kombinatoren i STLC: Y er ikke typbar! (krever rekursive typer eller μ-typer)
//   i untyped LC: Y f = f(Y f) -> beregner fikspunkter av f
// de Bruijn: λx.λy. x y -> λ.λ. 1 0 (indeks teller binders utenfra, starter 0)
//   substituering: t[0:=u] shifter indekser i u for binding-dybde

// This defines the lambda calculus: syntax with de Bruijn indices, capture-avoiding
// substitution, beta/eta reduction, Church-Rosser confluence, reduction strategies
// (CBN/CBV/CBNeed), Church encodings of data, Y-combinator, and simply-typed lambda calculus.

