// Semantic direction:
// modul_typeteori gives a formal foundation for ML-style module systems.
// ml_signatur_mt specifies the interface of a module: types, values, and sub-modules.
// ml_opak_type hides a type's definition in the signature, enabling abstraction.
// ml_type_deling constrains modules to share a specific type definition.
// sig_avhengig_funktor is a funktor where the output type depends on the input structure.
// sealing_operatør (m :> S) restricts module m to the interface S, hiding internals.
// ascription_operatør (m : S) typechecks m against S without hiding anything.
// generativ_app creates a new abstract type on each application — two calls give incompatible types.
// applikativ_app returns the same type for equal arguments — enables safe sharing.
// first_class_modul allows modules to be stored in data structures and passed to functions.
// modul_pack wraps a module as a first-class value; modul_unpack extracts it.
// rekursive_moduler enable mutually recursive modules with the rec keyword.
// realisasjonsrelasjon: a structure S realizes a signature Σ if S provides everything Σ requires.
// principal_signature is the strongest signature realizable by a given structure.
// avhengig_sum_mt: a module is a dependent pair (t, {ops on t}) — the dependent sum perspective.
// mixin_komposisjon assembles modules by combining traits with late binding.
// diamond_problem_mixin: trait conflict when two traits define the same method.
// relaxed_value_restriction loosens the restriction on polymorphic values at module boundaries.

// Primitive flow:
// Signatur definisjon: sig Map { type t; val tom: t; val sett_inn: int → int → t → t }
// Struktur implementasjon: struct Map { type t = ... impl; val tom = ...; val sett_inn = ... }
// Sealing: let M = Map :> SIG  -- M.t er nå opak, impl skjult
// Funktor: functor MakeSet(M : Map) : Set = struct type element = M.key; ... end
//   generativ: MakeSet(M1) og MakeSet(M2) gir ukompatible Set-typer
//   applikativ: MakeSet(M) alltid gir samme Set-type for samme M
// First-class: type any_map = { M: module type of Map }
//   pack M = {M = HashMap} : any_map -- pak inn
//   unpack (let module M = m.M in M.sett_inn 1 2 M.tom) -- pakk ut

// This defines module type theory: ML signatures/structures/functors with dependent types,
// opaque and transparent ascription/sealing, generative vs applicative functor application,
// first-class modules with pack/unpack, recursive modules, mixin composition, and the
// denotational realization semantics via dependent sums.

