// Semantic direction:
// FLP_umulighet: Fischer-Lynch-Paterson (1985) — no deterministic algorithm solves consensus in
//   a fully asynchronous system even with one crash failure. Fundamental impossibility result.
// bivalent_argument: a configuration is bivalent if both outcomes (0 or 1) remain possible;
//   FLP shows an initial bivalent config exists and can always be extended while staying bivalent.
// Paxos: Lamport (1989) — prepare/promise/accept/commit phases; safe under crash failures.
// Raft: Ongaro-Ousterhout (2014) — understandability-first Paxos variant; same safety guarantees.
// PBFT_protokoll: Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance — tolerates ⌊(n−1)/3⌋ Byzantine nodes; O(n²) messages.
// HotStuff_protokoll: linear message complexity BFT; basis for many blockchain consensus protocols.
// CAP_teorem: Brewer (2000) — a distributed system can guarantee at most 2 of: Consistency, Availability, Partition-tolerance.
// Lamport_klokker: logical clocks L(e) such that e→f implies L(e) < L(f) — captures causality order.
// vektor_klokker: V[i] tracks events at each process — V(e) < V(f) iff e causally precedes f.
// selvstabilisering: Dijkstra (1974) — from any state, system converges to a valid state in finite time.

// Primitive flow:
// Paxos fase 1: Proposer sender Prepare(n) → Acceptor lover å ikke akseptere n' < n
// Paxos fase 2: Proposer sender Accept(n, v) → Acceptor aksepterer hvis ingen løfte brytes
// konsensus: alle korrekte prosesser beslutter samme verdi v ∈ {foreslåtte verdier}

