// Semantic direction:
// komplekse_nettverk: real-world networks (web, social, biological) share structural properties
//   — power-law degree, small world, clustering — that random graphs lack.
// Barabási_Albert_modell: preferential attachment — new nodes attach preferentially to high-degree
//   nodes → power-law degree distribution P(k) ∝ k^{-3}.
// Watts_Strogatz_modell: start with lattice, rewire edges randomly — gives small-world + clustering.
// skalfrie_nettverk: robust to random failures (most nodes have low degree) but fragile to targeted
//   hub removal — explains internet resilience and Achilles heel.
// SIR_modell: S→I→R with rates β,γ; epidemic if R₀ = β/γ > 1; final size solves 1−S∞ = 1−e^{−R₀(1−S∞)}.
// grunntall_reproduksjon: R₀ > 1 → epidemic; R₀ < 1 → extinction; herd immunity at 1−1/R₀.
// perkolasjonsteori: giant component emerges at p = 1/⟨k⟩ — phase transition in network connectivity.
// greedy_innflytelse: Kempe-Kleinberg-Tardos (2003) — greedy gives (1−1/e)-approximation for influence max.
// CELF_optimalisering: lazy evaluation cuts influence maximisation time by 700× in practice.
// cascading_failure: failure of a few hubs triggers chain reaction — power grid, financial contagion.

// Primitive flow:
// SIR: dS/dt = -βSI/N, dI/dt = βSI/N - γI, dR/dt = γI
// R₀ = β/γ: R₀ > 1 → epidemi; flokkimmunitet ved 1 - 1/R₀ andel immune
// perkolasjon: fjern noder med sanns. 1-p → kjempelkomponent forsvinner ved p_c = 1/⟨k⟩

